With over 170 species distributed across the tropics and subtropics worldwide and 47 nominate species occurring in India , the genus
Hemidactylus
is one of the most speciose gekkonid genera (
Uetz et al. 2021
). Increased interest in and research into this group has led to many new species descriptions, taxonomic revisions, and distribution extensions (Giri 2008; Giri & Bauer 2008 ;
Giri et al . 2009
; Mahony 2009 , 2011 ;
Gaikwad et al. 2010
;
Purkayastha et al. 2010
; Ganesh & Chandramouli 2010 ;
Agarwal et al . 2011
;
Bauer et al . 2012
;
Pal et al. 2013
;
Srinivasulu et al . 2014
; Mirza & Sanap 2014 ;
Kumar et al. 2015
;
Murthy et al. 2015
; Mirza & Raju 2017 ;
Ganesh et al. 2017
;
Agarwal et al. 2018
;
Chaitanya et al. 2018
;
Mirza et al. 2018
;
Srikanthan et al. 2018
;
Agarwal et al. 2019
;
Khandekar et al. 2020a
; Lajmi et al. 2020). With the advancement of molecular phylogenetics over the past decade, our understanding of radiations and relationships within Indian
Hemidactylus
and the detection of cryptic species have increased substantially ( Bansal & Karanth 2010 , 2013 ;
Bauer et al. 2010a
, b;
Lajmi et al. 2016
, 2019;
Chaitanya et al. 2019
;
Agarwal et al. 2020a
).

To infer putative species within the
H. flaviviridis
complex, we used species delimitation based on the Bayesian Poisson Tree Process (bPTP), implemented on the Species Delimitation web server (http://species.h-its.org/ptp/;
Zhang et al. 2013
), excluding the outgroup taxon to optimise the process. The analysis was run for 100,000 generations with a thinning parameter of 100 and a burnin of 0.25.

